                </a></li></ul></div><p><strong>Figure 2.  <span>Cost-effectiveness acceptability curves from the health care (A) and societal (B) perspective.</span></strong></p><a id="article1.body1.sec3.sec1.fig2.caption1.p1" name="article1.body1.sec3.sec1.fig2.caption1.p1"></a><p>Vertical lines indicate the threshold where genotypic antiretroviral resistance testing and treatment optimization based on expert opinion have the same probability of being cost-effective. At a higher willingness to pay per QALY gained (e.g. at $US 50000/QALY) genotypic antiretroviral resistance testing has a higher probability of being cost-effective than expert opinion alone.</p>
